    "content": "---\nname: business-opportunity\ndescription: Size and assess Staycation business opportunities with a product-management lens centered on GMV. Use when the user wants to evaluate, compare, or document a new feature, growth idea, segment expansion, or marketplace opportunity.\nlicense: MIT\n---\n\n# Business Opportunity\n\nAssess how an idea could create GMV and frame it in a way that is useful for product, design, engineering, marketing, and leadership.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Clarify the opportunity, target users, constraints, and unknowns.\n2. State the assumptions required to size the opportunity if data is missing.\n3. Explain the likely GMV levers:\n   - Conversion rate\n   - Average order value\n   - Booking frequency\n   - New user acquisition\n   - New segment activation\n4. Provide an order-of-magnitude sizing when possible. Use ranges, not fake precision.\n5. Suggest follow-up analyses, experiments, or data pulls when the opportunity is still uncertain.\n\n## Output\n\nUse this structure by default.\n\n### Opportunity assessment\n\n#### Objective\n\nExplain the business objective and connect it clearly to GMV or a leading indicator.\n\n#### Key results\n\nDefine 2 to 4 measurable outcomes that would indicate success.\n\n#### Customer problem\n\nDescribe the user problem in plain language.\n\n#### Target market\n\nDescribe the main user segment or segments to target.\n\n## Style\n\n- Write short, factual sentences.\n- Surface assumptions and hypotheses explicitly.\n- Keep the reasoning accessible to mixed audiences.\n- Add clarifying questions only when they materially affect sizing or prioritization."
